uppress demand for snacks and possibly some other things, and by lots of ne=
ws stories and research notes=C2=A0about what Ozempic would do to the stock=
 prices of snack companies. But of course I always conceded that Ozempic is=
=C2=A0not=C2=A0a universal demand suppressant. It would be interesting if s=
omeone invented such a drug, and it is a fun thought experiment to imagine =
that Ozempic=C2=A0is such a drug. Mostly it=E2=80=99s a weight-loss drug, t=
hough.
I have fun imagining this stuff, and so do a lot of other people, so you ca=
n read a lot about the effects that Ozempic might have on snack makers (bad=
) or medical device companies (bad) or airlines (good: skinnier passengers =
use less fuel). But it is possible that these stories all really mean =E2=
=80=9Cit is fun to think about this=E2=80=9D rather than =E2=80=9Cthis is a=
 real effect that will matter to these companies=E2=80=99 bottom line.=E2=
=80=9D Anyway the Wall Street Journal makes fun of this whole idea:

Call it the Ozempic effect. A new generation of highly effective weight-los=
s and diabetes drugs known as GLP-1s has led to fanciful assumptions on Wal=
l Street that spell doom for companies that have profited from America=E2=
=80=99s obesity problem. It has also led to speculation that gigantic oppor=
tunities await those that would benefit from the aggregate weight loss.
Wild scenarios conjured up by analysts include the notion that junk-food co=
mpanies might pivot to selling carrot sticks and airlines might save on gas=
 owing to lighter passengers. References to GLP drugs have shot higher on c=
ompany earnings calls over the past 12 months, according to Factiva.
The reaction on Wall Street has been extreme, creating opportunities for co=
oler heads, some analysts and investors say. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Because of a va=
riety of constraints, the days that those drugs truly make America a slimme=
r nation are nowhere near. Among the obstacles are the high sticker price o=
