Absolutely not,  come on:

The Securities and Exchange Commission [Wednesday] charged SafeMoon LLC, it=
s creator Kyle Nagy, SafeMoon US LLC, and the companies=E2=80=99 Chief Exec=
utive Officer, John Karony, and Chief Technology Officer, Thomas Smith, for=
 perpetrating a massive fraudulent scheme through the unregistered sale of =
the crypto asset security, SafeMoon. According to the SEC=E2=80=99s complai=
nt, the Defendants promised to take the price of the token =E2=80=9CSafely =
to the moon,=E2=80=9D but instead of delivering profits, they wiped out bil=
lions in market capitalization, withdrew crypto assets worth more than $200=
 million from the project, and misappropriated investor funds for personal =
use.
=E2=80=9CDecentralized finance claims to deliver transparency and predictab=
le outcomes, but unregistered offerings lack the disclosures and accountabi=
lity that the law demands, and they attract scammers like Kyle Nagy, who us=
e these vulnerabilities to enrich themselves at the expense of others,=E2=
=80=9D said David Hirsch, Chief of the SEC Enforcement Division=E2=80=99s C=
rypto Assets and Cyber Unit (CACU).

There is also a  criminal case; Karony and Smith were arrested, but =E2=80=
=9CNagy remains at large.=E2=80=9D Look, if someone asks you to invest in a=
 thing that they will take =E2=80=9Csafely to the moon,=E2=80=9D and you gi=
ve them money, (1) sure sure sure they should immediately go to jail but (2=
) so should you. Absolutely not! Ooooooooh, thanks to the magic of crypto, =
we have found a new way to make money turn into much more money with no ris=
k, ooooh. Jail for all of you! I tell you, man,   when I run the SEC=C2=A0=
=E2=80=A6
The basic mechanism of a lot of decentralized finance projects is=C2=A0a=C2=
=A0Ponzi scheme with some fairly standard complexification:
=09You invent a token, BoxCoin or whatever,
  [7]
=C2=A0and sell it to people.=09People who own BoxCoin get paid a yield =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9CAPY,=E2=80=9D for =E2=80=9Cannual percentage yield,=E2=
=80=9D is the standard term =E2=80=94=C2=A0in BoxCoin, or perhaps in some r=
elated crypto token.=09Like, you know, every 12 hours you get 10% more toke=
ns or whatever.=C2=A0=09People are like =E2=80=9Clook at how high the yield=
 on BoxCoin is, I=E2=80=99d better get some.=E2=80=9D=09They buy it, and th=
e price goes up.=09Now the yield looks even better: Now you have 100 BoxCoi=
ns worth, like, 2 cents each, but in 12 hours you=E2=80=99ll have 110 BoxCo=
ins worth 3 cents each. What a yield!

The trick is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I mean, it is all a trick =E2=80=A6=C2=A0but on=
e trick is to hype it up and=C2=A0get people to buy BoxCoins, so that yield=
 looks like an actual monetary yield rather than just the proliferation of =
worthless numbers, and the other trick is to get people not to=C2=A0sell=C2=
=A0BoxCoins, because if they sell it all collapses.
We have talked about this so many times. This is, for instance,   Hex. It i=
s   Terra and Luna. It is, perhaps most beautifully,   OlympusDAO, whose tr=
ick to stop people from selling was to explain to them, in winkingly preten=
tious game-theoretic terms, that if everybody bought and nobody sold then t=
hey=E2=80=99d all make money, but if they sold they=E2=80=99d all lose mone=
y. =E2=80=9C(3, 3)=E2=80=9D was for a while an important crypto  meme. I ca=
nnot adequately express how insane 2021 was.
Anyway SafeMoon=E2=80=99s=C2=A0trick was that if you sold your SafeMoon tok=
ens, the SafeMoon protocol would take a 10% =E2=80=9Ctax.=E2=80=9D Thus buy=
ing was good and selling was bad, which kept a floor on the price. (For a w=
hile.) Half of the 10% tax was used to pay the yield on the other tokens: I=
f you=C2=A0sell=C2=A0your tokens, you pay 10%; if you=C2=A0hold=C2=A0your t=
okens, you get half of the money that the sellers pay. This creates a furth=
er incentive to hold, and the yield that makes the whole thing attractive. =
This was called =E2=80=9Creflection=E2=80=9D; SafeMoon=E2=80=99s  whitepape=
r said:
[T]he reflect mechanism encourages holders to hang onto their tokens to gar=
ner higher kick-backs which are based upon a percentages [sic] carried out =
and dependent upon the total tokens held by the owner. In theory, with the =
manual burn function =E2=80=A6 even a small holder at the beginning could p=
otentially walk away with big money at the end of the token=E2=80=99s lifes=
pan.
The other half of the 10% tax was allegedly stolen by the developers, which=
 is why they are in jail now.

