<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/33234558.258414/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTEtMDEvdHJhZGUtdGhlLW5ld3MtdGhlbi1wdWJsaXNoLWl0P2NtcGlk=
PUJCRDExMDIyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV=
0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMTEwMiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cBd39a5567" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked yesterday</a> about insider trading,=
 journalism, and a startup hedge fund / investigative journalism outlet cal=
led Hunterbrook, which plans to report big investigative stories, trade on =
them, and then publish them. I want to mention a few bits of follow-up.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">First, I got an email from someone who works a=
t a financial firm saying<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important=
; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We=E2=80=99ve observed a certain v=
ery low-quality source=C2=A0move stocks with low-quality takeover rumors. G=
iven the impact the source can=C2=A0have, we wanted to subscribe. So we sen=
t them our usual due diligence questionnaire=C2=A0that included the questio=
n =E2=80=9Cdo you seek out inside info,=E2=80=9D to which they replied=C2=
=A0=E2=80=9Clol yes of course that=E2=80=99s the point=E2=80=9D (paraphrasi=
ng). So of course then we can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0subscribe.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But they <em>can </em>subscribe to the Wall St=
reet Journal, and to the Bloomberg Terminal, even though Journal and Bloomb=
erg News reporters do call up sources inside companies to try to get nonpub=
lic information and then publish it. If you work at a hedge fund, you are n=
ot supposed to trade on inside information, and it is standard practice to =
make sure that your=C2=A0<em>data vendors=C2=A0</em>do not give you=C2=A0in=
side information. If one of your data vendors is a financial information se=
rvice that seeks out inside information, that=E2=80=99s bad. If it=E2=80=99=
s a newspaper that does investigative reporting, that=E2=80=99s fine.=C2=A0=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Second, I wrote yesterday about the line betwe=
en journalism and insider trading, and I suggested that the line is probabl=
y some (fairly small) number of subscribers. If you find stuff out and emai=
l it to five hedge funds, that feels like you are a =E2=80=9Cconsultant=E2=
=80=9D and it=E2=80=99s insider trading. If you email it to 100 newsletter =
subscribers, 90 of whom are hedge funds, you=E2=80=99re probably okay. Not =
legal advice!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A reader pointed me to arguably the leading co=
urt case on the matter, involving Reorg Research.<a class=3D"footnote-index=
" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display=
: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a> This was not an insider trading case: Reorg Research Inc. <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33234558.258414/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAxNy8wNi8yMS9ueXJlZ2lvbi9ueS1hcHBlYWxzLWNvdXJ0LXNoaWVsZ=
C1sYXctam91cm5hbGlzdHMtcmVvcmcuaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB14d7b4b6" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;"> is a =E2=80=9Ccorporate intelligence company=E2=80=9D</a> covering b=
ankruptcy and distressed debt, and it sent subscribers two alerts about Mur=
ray Energy Corp. Murray =E2=80=9Csuspected that the unnamed sources were so=
me of its own investors who, the executives believed, had revealed the info=
rmation despite having signed confidentiality agreements,=E2=80=9D so it as=
ked a judge to force Reorg to reveal its sources. Reorg said, no, we are jo=
urnalists, and New York=E2=80=99s Shield Law protects us from having to rev=
eal our sources. Many journalistic organizations, including Bloomberg LP, s=
upported Reorg, and a New York appeals court agreed: Reorg was doing journa=
lism. At the time, it had =E2=80=9Cabout 375 subscribers who =E2=80=98manag=
e trillions of dollars in assets=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D and paid=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cb=
etween $30,000 and $120,000 a year=E2=80=9D for subscriptions. So the line =
between journalism and insider trading is probably lower than 375 subscribe=
rs.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Finally, here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/33234558.258414/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYXhpb3MuY29tL25=
ld3NsZXR0ZXJzL2F4aW9zLXByby1yYXRhLTIyOThmYmU3LTFhOTYtNGRkMS05OTk0LWYyZmJhYj=
I4YjRmZi5odG1s/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCc0538cb2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Dan Primack at A=
xios</a> with more detail on Hunterbrook=E2=80=99s model, which involves gl=
obal coverage, commodity and currency trading, and being very very careful =
not to do insider trading<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important=
; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The key here is that despite the involvement o=
f media vets, including on the founding team and in its investor ranks, thi=
s=C2=A0<em>is not</em>=C2=A0a journalistic endeavor. Specifically, the "res=
earchers" will not be speaking with sources inside of companies for the sak=
e of discovering non-public information and then trading on such knowledge,=
 because that would be a clear violation of securities regulations.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Instead, Hunterbrook researchers will need to =
rely on publicly available information, which likely means the new ranks wi=
ll be stuffed full of open-source, big data journalists and individuals on =
the ground in geographies with relatively little traditional media coverage=
. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some investigations will focus on accounting, =
much as do traditional short-sellers like Hindenburg Research, but also int=
o other areas of malfeasance (environmental, humanitarian, etc.).</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A story will then be prepared, including fact-=
checking and legal compliance, before being turned over to a separate inves=
tment team to determine if there's a trade to be made before publishing.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One reason a story could publish without a tra=
de is that the researcher uncovered non-public information (i.e., acted lik=
e a journalist).</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If the story is=C2=A0<em>too=C2=A0</em>good, y=
ou can=E2=80=99t trade on it.</p>
